FPP - Ch. 3 Exercises

The Forecasters Toolbox
Dan Hong | dnaeye@gmail.com

The following are my answers to the exercises in the excellent book Forecasting: Principles & Practice by Rob J Hyndman and George Athanasopoulos.

library(fpp2)

BoxCox.lambda(mcopper)

2. Why is a Box-Cox transformation unhelpful for the cangas data?

autoplot(BoxCox(cangas, BoxCox.lambda(cangas)))

It could not minimize the seasonal variations very much.

3. What Box-Cox transformation would you select for your retail data?

retaildata <- readxl::read_excel("retail.xlsx", skip=1)
retail <- ts(retaildata[,"A3349335T"], frequency=12, start=c(1982,4))
BoxCox.lambda(retail)
[1] 0.193853

Using BoxCox.lambda to automatically find the best lambda, it computed 0.193853, so a transformation is recommeded for this series.

4. For each of the following series (dole, usdeaths, bricksq), make a graph of the data. If transforming seems appropriate, do so and describe the effect.

autoplot(dole)

lambda_dole <- BoxCox.lambda(dole)
autoplot(BoxCox(dole, lambda_dole))

lambda = 0.3290922

Transforming the series made the seasonal variations early in the series, from 1956 to 1975, more apparent and reduced the scale of the variance later in the series, especially around 1983.

autoplot(usdeaths)

lambda_usdeaths <- BoxCox.lambda(usdeaths)
autoplot(BoxCox(usdeaths, lambda_usdeaths))

lambda = -0.0336377

Although the automatic BoxCox.lambda function returned a value other than 1, it did not change the shape of the time series.

autoplot(bricksq)

lambda_bricksq <- BoxCox.lambda(bricksq)
autoplot(BoxCox(bricksq, lambda_bricksq))

lambda = 0.2548929

In this case, the Box-Cox transformation helped somewhat to normalize the seasonal variance.

5. Calculate the residuals from a seasonal naive forecast applied to the quarterly Australian beer production data from 1992.

beer <- window(ausbeer, start=1992)
fc <- snaive(beer)
autoplot(fc)

res <- residuals(fc)
autoplot(res)

Test if the residuals are white noise and normally distributed.

checkresiduals(fc)

    Ljung-Box test

data:  Residuals from Seasonal naive method
Q* = 32.269, df = 8, p-value = 8.336e-05

Model df: 0.   Total lags used: 8

The residuals are likely white noise, because there are no discernible patterns in residuals plot. The mean is -1.57; this bias can easily be adjusted by adding it to all forecasts. The ACF shows only autocorrelation at lag 4, which may have been a false positive. The residuals are roughly normally distributed in the last graph, but there is a longer left tail. All results show that forecasts using this model will be good, but prediction intervals computed assuming a normal distribution may be inaccurate.

6. Repeat Exer. 5 with WWWusage and bricksq datasets.

frequency(WWWusage)
[1] 1

There is no observed frequency in WWWusage, so the naive method will be used.

fc <- naive(WWWusage)
autoplot(fc)

res <- residuals(fc)
autoplot(res)

Test residuals.

checkresiduals(res)

There is no obvious pattern in the residuals, suggesting white noise. The mean residual is 6.8344371, which can be simply added to forecasts to adjust for bias. The ACF chart shows significant autocorrelation decaying through lag 6 and then again from lag 18, suggesting that the series is non-stationary.

This can be supported by running a Ljung-Box test with a lag, or h, of 10, as suggested in 3.3 Residual diagnostics for non-seasonal data.

Box.test(res, lag=10, fitdf=0, type="Lj")

    Box-Ljung test

data:  res
X-squared = 145.58, df = 10, p-value <
2.2e-16

The low p-value (less than 0.05) indicates there is a trend in the data.

frequency(bricksq)
[1] 4

Quarterly frequency is observed in bricksq, so the snaive method will be used.

fc <- snaive(bricksq)
autoplot(fc)

res <- residuals(fc)
autoplot(res)

Test residuals.

checkresiduals(res)

The residuals plot displays no pattern. The ACF plot shows decaying autocorrelation for lags 2-3 and then again from lag 5 to 10, suggesting there is some information left in the residuals that can be used for computing forecasts. The residuals histogram plot is left skewed due to the long tail to the left.

7. Are the following statements true or false? Explain your answer.

a. Good forecast methods should have normally distributed residuals.
False. Its useful for calculating prediction intervals, but not necessary.

b. A model with small residuals will give good forecasts.
False. The size of the residuals is not a reliable indication of how large true forecast errors are likely to be. The accuracy of forecasts can only be determined by considering how well a model performs on new data that were not used when fitting the model.

c. The best measure of forecast accuracy is MAPE.
False. It is probably the most common one, but not necessarily best. Actually, a better method might be measuring RMSE using time series cross-validation.

d. If your model doesnt forecast well, you should make it more complicated.
False. Adding more variables may lead to a model that fits the historical data perfectly, but it will not produce good forecasts into the future.

e. Always choose the model with the best forecast accuracy as measured on the test set.
True.

8. For your retail time series (from Exercise 3 in Section 2.10), do the following:

8a. Split retail time series into training and test sets.

retaildata <- readxl::read_excel("retail.xlsx", skip=1)

myts.train <- window(myts, end=c(2010,12))

autoplot(myts) +
  autolayer(myts.train, series="Training") +
  autolayer(myts.test, series="Test")

fc <- snaive(myts.train)

The low p-value from the Ljung-Box test indicates that there is still trend in the series. This is supported by the residuals plot, which exhibits and upward trend with increasing variance. Also, the ACF plot shows decaying autocorrelation through about lag 12 and then a plateau of positive lags after that. The histogram of residuals tails to the right.

9. visnights contains quarterly visitor nights (in millions) from 1998 to 2016 for twenty regions of Australia.

9a. Use window() to create three training sets for visnights[,"QLDMetro"], omitting the last 1, 2 and 3 years; call these train1, train2, and train3, respectively.

train1 <- window(visnights[, "QLDMetro"], end=c(2015, 4))
train2 <- window(visnights[, "QLDMetro"], end=c(2014, 4))
train3 <- window(visnights[, "QLDMetro"], end=c(2013, 4))

9b. Compute one year of forecasts for each training set using the snaive() method.

fc1 <- snaive(train1, h=4)
fc2 <- snaive(train2, h=4)
fc3 <- snaive(train3, h=4)

10. Use the Dow Jones index (data set dowjones) to do the following:

10a. Produce a time plot of the dowjones series.

autoplot(dowjones)

10b. Produce forecasts using the drift method and plot them.
10c. Show that the forecasts are identical to extending the line drawn between the first and last observations.

dj_drift <- rwf(dowjones, drift = TRUE)
autoplot(dj_drift) + geom_segment(aes(x=0, y=dowjones[1], xend=78, yend=tail(dowjones,1)[1], col="simple line"))

10d. Try using some of the other benchmark functions to forecast the same data set. Which do you think is best? Why?

dj_train <- window(dowjones, end=72)
dj_test <- window(dowjones, start=73)
dj_drift <- rwf(dj_train, drift = TRUE)
dj_drift_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(dj_drift, dj_test))
dj_naive <- naive(dj_train)
autoplot(dj_naive)

dj_naive_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(dj_naive, dj_test))
dj_snaive <- snaive(dj_train)
autoplot(dj_snaive)

dj_snaive_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(dj_snaive, dj_test))

The MAPE measures of the various forecast models are as follows:

  • Drift: 0.8086951
  • Naive: 0.4026
  • Snaive: 0.1017677

For the 6-day forecast period (i.e., Day 73-78), the model with the best accuracy was the seasonal naive model.

11. Consider the daily closing IBM stock prices (data set ibmclose).

11a. Produce some plots of the data in order to become familiar with it.

autoplot(ibmclose)

autoplot(diff(ibmclose))

11b. Split the data into a training set of 300 observations and a test set of 69 observations.

ibm_train <- window(ibmclose, end=300)
ibm_test <- window(ibmclose, start=301, end=370)
'end' value not changed

11c. Try using various benchmark methods to forecast the training set and compare the results on the test set. Which method did best?

ibm_naive <- naive(ibm_train, h=69)
autoplot(ibm_naive) + autolayer(ibm_test)

ibm_naive_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(ibm_naive, ibm_test))
ibm_snaive <- snaive(ibm_train, h=69)
autoplot(ibm_snaive) + autolayer(ibm_test)

ibm_snaive_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(ibm_snaive, ibm_test))
ibm_drift <- rwf(ibm_train, drift = TRUE, h=69)
autoplot(ibm_drift) + autolayer(ibm_test)

ibm_drift_acc <- as.data.frame(accuracy(ibm_drift, ibm_test))

The MAPE of the various benchmark models are:

  • naive: 4.6681858
  • snaive: 4.6681858
  • drift: 3.7078875

So, the model with the best MAPE was the drift one.

11d. Check the residuals of your preferred method. Do they resemble white noise?

checkresiduals(ibm_drift)

    Ljung-Box test

data:  Residuals from Random walk with drift
Q* = 22.555, df = 9, p-value = 0.007278

Model df: 1.   Total lags used: 10

The residuals resemble white noise, but the p-value from the Ljung-Box test was low, indicating that it is not white noise and that there is some autocorrelation through lag 10; the residuals plot had points oscillating around a mean of 0; the ACFs for most lags (except lag 6) were within the interval of significance, and the residual distribution plot was mostly normal.
